00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:35,000
Oh well the apparatus is what is called an electron defraction unit.

107
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:50,000
It consists of the essential feature of it is an electron gun that will produce a well-colonated beam of electrons at the potential of about 60 kilobols.

108
00:19:50,000 --> 00:20:00,000
So it's a very energetic beam on the scale of the way chemistry operates.

109
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:06,000
That beam is admitted to a large vacuum chamber.

110
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:14,000
In my apparatus the whole thing has mounted vertically so the beam comes down into this vacuum chamber.

111
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:30,000
And at the bottom of the beam let's say is a detecting beam which is in my case photographic film in those days of photographic plates but it's no photographic film.

112
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:44,000
And this photographic film is 8 x 10 inches square and is perpendicular to the beam and is moved into position by mechanism that I built into the apparatus.

113
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:56,000
And the apparatus is designed to study the structures of molecules and the gas phase by diffracting this beam of electrons from them.

114
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:13,000
So we have a long nozzle that protrudes into the apparatus with a tip that passes that stops just about a millimeter short of where there's very fine high-powered electron beam is coming down.

115
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Now if in this nozzle which is a two with a fine tip on it you admit a gas into the chamber the gas shoots out the nozzle tip intersects the electron beam at right angles and produces what is called a diffraction pattern.

116
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:45,000
This diffraction pattern consists of what happens is of course it's recorded on this photographic film at the underneath the nozzle and perpendicular to the beam.

117
00:21:45,000 --> 00:22:12,000
So the diffraction pattern is recorded on this in a set of diffuse rings of varying intensity and the spacing of these rings and their shapes of the pattern contain all the structural information about the length of the interatomic distances in the molecule.

118
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:24,000
And so we take these patterns and we analyze them and out of that we can deduce the intimate details of the structures of these molecules in the gas phase.

119
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:36,000
That is essentially it's a structure of a single molecule because so far apart they don't interact with one another as they shoot into the apparatus.

120
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:43,000
