180
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:18,000
So what were the techniques that you used to analyze the detection patterns initially?

181
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:26,000
Well, yes, that's a good question. I don't know how much of the technology I ought to go into.

182
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:44,000
Essentially, you're faced with this photographic film, which you hold it up to the light. You see this beautiful pattern of circular rings of varying intensity, very diffuse, easily recognized going out from a central point.

183
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:53,000
And all the information about the structure of the molecules contained, as I said earlier, in the spacings and the shapes of these rings.

184
00:30:53,000 --> 00:31:01,000
The question then you're really asking is how do you go from that to determine how the molecules put together?

185
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:14,000
Well, it turns out that these rings are related to the structure of the molecule by some, according to theory, by in a rather simple way.

186
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:35,000
Keep it as simple as I possibly can. Every interatomic distance in the molecule creates an effect on this film, a pattern that consists of nothing more than a sine wave, going from the middle out.

187
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:41,000
The sine wave just goes up and down, up and down, up and down, all the way out to the end of the photographic plate.

188
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:50,000
So if you have a die-accomming molecule, all rings in their intensity would look like a sine wave, just from the beginning, up, down, down, down, down.

189
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:59,000
The spacing would be identical between them, aside from some geometric factors that I don't have to go into.

190
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:15,000
All you have to do is to measure the frequency, oh, I should say that the farther apart the two atoms are that are giving rise to this sine wave, the greater the frequency of the sine wave.

191
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:21,000
So two atoms that are far apart like this give a sine wave that goes up and down very rapidly.

192
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:31,000
Two atoms that are very close together will give a sine wave that has a very long wavelength.

193
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:43,000
So you'll see very few rings. So all you'd have to do is to measure the spacing between these rings, and that is related by theory to how far apart the atoms are.

194
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:50,000
Well, now that's for a die-atomic, let's say that's the case for a die-atomic molecule, you only have one sine wave.

195
00:32:50,000 --> 00:33:02,000
The die-atomic molecule vibrates, and so the atoms are not rigid, they're moving back and forth away from one another, like two balls on a spring.

196
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:18,000
And of course that means that the distance is in constant. Well, it turns out according to theory to a good approximation, this sine wave instead of having constant amplitude all the way up, dies off due to this vibration.

197
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:27,000
So you measure the dying off of the sine wave, and that tells you how big the amplitude of this vibration is.

198
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:41,000
So we learn about two things, the distances between the atoms on the average, and we learn about how much they're moving with respect to one another by measuring the damping off of the sine wave.

199
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:56,000
Well, of course there aren't many die-atomic molecules left to study, but every that problem, or rather the theory that I mentioned applies to just the pairs of atoms.

200
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:07,000
So if you have a molecule that has more than just two atoms in it, you're going to have more than two distances, more than one distance.

201
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:13,000
Every pair of atoms in the molecule gives rise to one of these sine waves.

202
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:25,000
So carbon dioxide is a linear molecule, is a carbon oxygen bond, and that gives rise to a single sine wave that goes out.

203
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:32,000
There are two of them, but they have exactly the same distance, so there are two sine waves that are right on top of one another.

204
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:37,000
Then you have the distance between the oxygen atoms, and that's twice as big.

205
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:51,000
So it generates a sine wave also, which has a frequency, twice as great to first approximation as the frequency of the carbon oxygen, because the distance is twice as long.

206
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:59,000
And that gives a sine wave that oscillates with twice the frequency of the first one, and then they're on top of one another.

207
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:05,000
So the pattern is no longer a simple sine wave, but a collection of two sine waves.

208
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:15,000
If you know how to separate out these sine waves and measure their frequencies, then you know exactly what the structure of this molecule is.

209
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:37,000
The two were bent, like NL2 is, NL2 would be entirely similar, but there you would find the distances between the oxygen atoms, the distance between the oxygen atoms, is not twice the distance between the nitrogen and oxygen, because it's a triangular molecule, like this.

210
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:46,000
So that oxygen distance would not be moving twice the frequency of the NL, but less than that.

211
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:57,000
So you can immediately determine that distance, and determine the nitrogen oxygen distance, and by comparing them, you know what the bond angle is in the molecule.

212
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:03,000
This simple account can be applied to molecules that are very, very complicated.

213
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:09,000
The entire problem, then, is just to separate out what these different sine waves are.

214
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:15,000
Construct yourself a model that will account for all of the distances, and then you have the structure of the molecule.

215
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:24,000
It is in practice considerably more complicated than I'm telling you, but that's essentially the features of the whole thing.

216
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:37,000
Now you ask how we do this. Well, we have to measure the frequencies, and to do that we have a scanner, what is called a microdensitometer.

217
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:51,000
The film is placed on the bed of this microdensitometer, and the film in the apparatus that I have, we have a mechanism that rotates the film around its center.

218
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:58,000
The purpose of this is that you are averaging the information around the entire circle.

219
00:36:58,000 --> 00:37:12,000
That is, if the densitometer consists of a beam that passes through the film, and a detector that measures how intense the light beam is as it comes through the film.

220
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:30,000
So, when the ring is intense, the light beam that comes through is much reduced, and when the film is more transparent, the beam that comes through there is more intense.

221
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:36,000
So, you get a recording of the blackness of the film.

222
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:56,000
So, this thing translates, and we have an electronic data accumulation system that measures the intensity of the blackness of the film as a function from the center outward.

223
00:37:56,000 --> 00:38:02,000
And that gives us digital data, and that is what we actually work with to analyze.

224
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:12,000
So, that is essentially it. And without having you in the laboratory for a week, I can't tell you much more that when I get clear here I don't think.

