684
01:24:31,000 --> 01:24:37,000
because after all, you're taking what is a continuous curve

685
01:24:37,000 --> 01:24:42,000
and you're sampling it at very small intervals along it,

686
01:24:42,000 --> 01:24:47,000
so you have points that correspond to this.

687
01:24:47,000 --> 01:24:53,000
Now, when the plate or film moves across the dense automator,

688
01:24:53,000 --> 01:24:57,000
it goes across the middle and back out on the other side.

689
01:24:57,000 --> 01:25:03,000
So we scan the film from one side to the other,

690
01:25:03,000 --> 01:25:08,000
but all the time it's rotating, which means that half of the film

691
01:25:08,000 --> 01:25:11,000
should be identical to the other half.

692
01:25:11,000 --> 01:25:14,000
And half of the trace should be identical to the other half.

693
01:25:14,000 --> 01:25:18,000
But since you're sampling by points, you can't make sure that these points are identical.

694
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:24,000
So you have to do something as we call, find the center.

695
01:25:24,000 --> 01:25:28,000
So we have a program that compares the two sides of this

696
01:25:28,000 --> 01:25:31,000
and determines where the center is.

697
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:34,000
And then it takes the data on one side and that on the other,

698
01:25:34,000 --> 01:25:37,000
interpolates if necessary, between the points,

699
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:40,000
adds them all together to give you a scan.

